#: resources/views/modules/statistics-chart/tabs/tree-health.phtml:121
msgid ""
"For every couple where both spouses have at least one parent recorded, the "
"widget walks each spouse's ancestor tree up to four generations and "
"intersects the two sets. A non-empty intersection means the couple share at "
"least one common ancestor — the classic signature of cousin marriage and "
"pedigree collapse."
msgstr ""
"For every couple where both spouses have at least one parent recorded, the "
"widget walks each spouse's ancestor tree up to four generations and "
"intersects the two sets. A non-empty intersection means the couple share at "
"least one common ancestor — the classic signature of cousin marriage and "
"pedigree collapse."

#: resources/views/modules/statistics-chart/tabs/places.phtml:57
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"For every individual the widget collects every distinct PLAC value that "
"appears on any of their level-1 events (BIRT, DEAT, BAPM, BURI, RESI, …) and "
"counts the unique places. Duplicates within the same individual (e.g. BIRT "
"and DEAT both in Hamburg) collapse to one place, so the count reflects "
"geographic mobility rather than how many events are recorded. The average is "
"across every individual with at least one PLAC sample; individuals with no "
"place data at all are excluded."
msgstr ""
"For every individual the widget collects every distinct PLAC value that "
"appears on any of their level-1 events (BIRT, DEAT, BAPM, BURI, RESI, …) and "
"counts the unique places. Duplicates within the same individual (e.g. BIRT "
"and DEAT both in Hamburg) collapse to one place, so the count reflects "
"geographic mobility rather than how many events are recorded. The average is "
"across every individual with at least one PLAC sample; individuals with no "
"place data at all are excluded. The distribution on the right shows how "
"those counts split across 1 / 2 / 3 / 4 / 5+ distinct places per person — a "
"high tail signals migrant ancestors, a heavy bar at \"1\" signals a "
"sedentary or sparsely-documented population."

#: resources/views/modules/statistics-chart/tabs/life-span.phtml:146
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"For every individual with both BIRT and DEAT julian-days the widget computes "
"the number of days lived; a death within five years (1826 days) of birth "
"counts as under-5 mortality. The line groups those children by their birth "
"century so the historical decline becomes visible (typical 1700s value 30-40 "
"percent, modern below 2 percent). Individuals with only BIRT or only DEAT "
"are silently excluded — we cannot determine survival without both anchors, "
"and including them would skew the rate. Per-century cohorts below 5 children "
"are suppressed because a single dead child would spike the line by more than "
"10 percentage points."
msgstr ""
"For every individual with both BIRT and DEAT julian-days the widget computes "
"the number of days lived; a death within five years (1826 days) of birth "
"counts as under-5 mortality. The tree-wide percentage is the share of such "
"children across the whole tree, and the LineChart on the right groups them "
"by their birth century so the historical decline becomes visible (typical "
"1700s value 30-40 percent, modern below 2 percent). Individuals with only "
"BIRT or only DEAT are silently excluded — we cannot determine survival "
"without both anchors, and including them would skew the rate. Per-century "
"cohorts below 5 children are suppressed because a single dead child would "
"spike the line by more than 10 percentage points."

#: resources/views/modules/statistics-chart/tabs/tree-health.phtml:117
msgid ""
"For every individual, this bucket counts how many generations of descendants "
"are recorded below them in the tree. Bucket 0 = leaf (no descendants), "
"bucket N = an individual whose deepest verified descendant is N generations "
"younger."
msgstr ""
"For every individual, this bucket counts how many generations of descendants "
"are recorded below them in the tree. Bucket 0 = leaf (no descendants), "
